@Node Getting_Going "Organiser Help: Getting Going"
@ToC Main
@{B}Getting Going@{UB}

When you first start Organiser, you will notice that a requester
appears asking you to @{" set the current date and time " Link Set_Date_And_Time}. It is
very important that you set this correctly, as Organiser uses it
to control alarms, reminders and so on.

Now you want to add a few items of information:
@{" Adding a Birthday " Link Add_Birthday}
@{" Add a Task        " Link Add_Task}

Then print them:
@{" Printing addresses      " Link Print_Addresses}
@{" Print my daily tasks    " Link Print_Tasks}
@{" Print some diary events " Link Print_Events}

You might need to change the views:
@{" See more events on a day " Link Views}

Lastly use the supplements:
@{" View an Organiser Supplement " Link Supplements}
@{" Install a Supplements        " Link Install_Supps}
@EndNode



@Node Tool_Types "Organiser Help: Tool Types"
@ToC Main
@{B}Organiser Tool Types@{UB}

Tool types are parameters used by the program. Tool types are
usually in the form of 'KEYWORD=argument'. Case differences do
not matter but you shouldn't use spaces.

Tool types can be commented, or disabled, so that Organiser
ignores them on loading. Commented tool types are enclosed in
parenthesis or preceded by a semi-colon (;).

Tool types are saved on the Project and settings files.


@{fg highlight}Tool Types For Program Icon Only@{fg text}

@{B}SETTINGS=<file>@{UB}
 This tool type specifies the Settings file and path to use.

@{B}PUBSCREEN=<screenname>@{UB}
 Specifies the public screen on which Organiser opena its
 display. You can use 'Workbench' to open Organiser on the
 Workbench screen.

@{B}PRINTDEVICE=<dosdevice>@{UB}
 This tool type specifies the DOS print device when printing
 from Organiser.
 
 This can be:
  PAR:  Prints straight to the parallel port.
  SER:  Prints straight to the serial port.
  PRT:  Prints through the Workbench printer driver system.

 (Other devices can be specified if, for example, you wish to
 print to a network)
 
 The <dosdevice> can also be a filename and path. This is
 different to the "Print To File" checkbox (@{" Print " Link Print} command,
 Project menu) in that it will contain printer formatting codes.

@{B}CLIPUNIT=<unitnumber>@{UB}
 This specifies the clip unit for Organisers clipboard. For more
 information refer to your Workbench Users Guide.


@{fg highlight}Tool Types For Project Icons Only@{fg text}

@{B}FILETYPE=<type>@{UB}
 Specifies the type of the file:
  ORGANISER            For an Organiser project file
  PREFS                For an Organiser Settings file
  ORGANISER|TEMPLATE   For an Organiser 'Diary Theme'.

 This tool type does not appear on the Organiser program icon.


@{fg highlight}Tool Types For Program Or Project Icons@{fg text}

@{B}CX_POPKEY=<hotkey>@{UB}
 Specifies the keyboard shortcut to bring the Organiser display
 to the front. It is also used to display Organiser when it has
 been @{" hidden " Link Hide}.

 You can use any of the function keys (F1 to F10) as a hotkey,
 or any other key from the keyboard (however, this will need to
 be preceeded by a qualifier).

 Acceptable qualfiers for Workbench 3 are:
  alt          Either Alt key
  Ralt         Right Alt only
  Lalt         Left Alt only
  shift        Either Shift key
  Rshift       Right Shift only
  Lshift       Left Shift only
  Lamiga       Left Amiga only
  Ramiga       Right Amiga only
  ctrl         Ctrl key
  NumericPad   Any key on the numeric keypad

 Acceptable qualfiers for Workbench 2 are:
  alt          Either Alt key
  Ralt         Right Alt only
  Lalt         Left Alt only
  shift        Either Shift key
  Rshift       Right Shift only
  Lshift       Left Shift only
  Lcommand     Left Amiga only
  Rcommand     Right Amiga only
  control      Ctrl key
  NumericPad   Any key on the numeric keypad

 Several qualifiers can be used together. But a qualifier must
 always be followed by a key from the keyboard.

 Some examples:
  CX_POPKEY=Alt F6
  CX_POPKEY=LAmiga Shift Ctrl D
  CX_POPKEY=F1
  CX_POPKEY=control alt #

 The hotkey appears after the file name in Organiser's window
 title bar as "(Hot Key = ...)".

@{B}CX_POPUP=<yes/no>@{UB}
 Specifies whether the Organiser display should be shown (yes)
 or hidden (no) on startup.

@{B}CX_PRIORITY=<-127 to 128>@{UB}
 Specifies the priority of the Commodity. Refer to your
 Workbench Users Guide for more information.
@EndNode



@Node Set_Date_And_Time "Organiser Help: 'Set Date and Time' requester"
@ToC Main
@{B}Setting the Date and Time@{UB}

The "Set Date and Time" requester appears each time you start
Organiser, to allow you to type the correct date and time before
proceeding.


@{fg highlight}Using The Requester@{fg text}

If the date and time are correct, just click OK. Otherwise, type
in the correct values before clicking OK.

If you have a built-in clock and wish to prevent this requester
from appearing every time you start Organsier, deselect the
"Set Date and Time on Startup" checkbox on the @{" General Settings " Link General_Settings}
requester ("Change Settings"-General, Settings menu), and then
choose @{" Save Settings " Link Save_Settings} (Settings menu).
@EndNode


@Node Project_Menu "Organiser Help: Project Menu"
@ToC Main
@{B}Project Menu@{UB}

The Project menu contains commands relating to the current
Organiser Project or File.

@{" New            " Link New}
@{" Open...        " Link Open}
@{" Save           " Link Save}
@{" Save As...     " Link Save}
@{" Import...      " Link Import}
@{" Export...      " Link Export}
@{" Print...       " Link Print}
@{" Hide           " Link Hide}
@{" About...       " Link About}
@{" Quit Organiser " Link Quit}
@EndNode


@Node New "Organiser Help: New Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}New command@{UB}

Choose New command (Project menu) to create a new, blank
Organiser project file. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-N.


@{fg highlight}Using New@{fg text}

You can only have one Organiser file open at a time. If you
already have an Organiser file open which has not yet been
saved, you will be warned and given the opportunity to save that
file before a new one is created.
@EndNode


@Node Open "Organiser Help: Open Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Open command@{UB}

Choose Open command (Project menu) to open a previously created
Organiser project file. Alternatively, click the Open icon on
the toolbar or press Right Amiga-O.


@{fg highlight}Using Open@{fg text}

Choosing this command will display a @{" file requester " Link FileRequester} from
which you select the Organiser file that you wish to open.

If a 'Diary Theme' is opened, the project will remain 'untitled'
so that you cannot accidently overwrite the original 'Diary
Theme' file.



@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}Open:@{UB} Opens the selected file.

@{B}Volumes:@{UB} Click to display volumes and assigns. Click again to
return to the file list.

@{B}Parent:@{UB} Click to display the contents of the parent drawer.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancel the file requester without opening any files.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Import command    " Link Import}
@{" Save command      " Link Save}
@{" 'Save As' command " Link Save_As}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 I cannot open my Supplements.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_File_1}

2 I have Day-By-Day and I want to use my project file with
  Organiser but I cannot get Organiser to open it.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_File_2}
  
3 I cannot import Names and Addresses into Organiser.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_File_3}
@EndNode


@Node Save "Organiser Help: Save Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Save command@{UB}

Choose Save command (Project menu) to save the current Organiser
file to disk. Alternatively, click the Save icon on the toolbar
or press Right Amiga-S.


@{fg highlight}Using Save@{fg text}

The file is saved using the current file name. If it is
untitled, a @{" file requester " Link FileRequester} will appear from which from which
you can specify the name and destination of the file.

If you wish to save the file to a different destination, or
using a different file name, use the @{" Save As " Link Save_As} command
(Project menu).


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Auto Save         " Link File_Settings}
@{" Export command    " Link Export}
@{" Hints And Tips    " Link Hints_And_Tips}
@{" Open command      " Link Open}
@{" 'Save As' command " Link Save_As}
@EndNode



@Node Save_As "Organiser Help: 'Save As' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Save As" command@{UB}

Choose "Save As" command (Project menu) to save the current
Organiser file to disk. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-A.


@{fg highlight}Using "Save As"@{fg text}

The "Save As" command will display a @{" file requester " Link FileRequester} from which you
can specify the name and destination of the file.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}Save:@{UB} Saves the file using the name and destination specified.

@{B}Volumes:@{UB} Click to display volumes and assigns. Click again to
return to the file list.

@{B}Parent:@{UB} Click to display the contents of the parent drawer.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancel the file requester without saving the file.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Auto Save      " Link File_Settings}
@{" Export command " Link Export}
@{" Hints And Tips " Link Hints_And_Tips}
@{" Open command   " Link Open}
@EndNode



@Node Import "Organiser Help: Import command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Import command@{UB}

Choose Import command (Project menu) to import information from
another source into Organiser.


@{fg highlight}Using Import@{fg text}

This command will allow you to import:

 ° Diary Events from Digita Day-By-Day into Organiser's Diary
   section.

 ° Addresses from Digita Mailshot Plus into Organiser's
   Addresses section.

 ° A plain ASCII text file into the Addresses section (if the
   file is suitably formatted as detailed below).

The ASCII file must include a header record. A header record is
a line at the top of the file detailing which fields are used,
what their names are, and in what order they appear.

The field names Organiser uses are as follows:
 NAME       VALUE

 Type       Either "Company", "Name" or "Name and Company"
 FirstName  Any text
 LastName   Any text
 Position   Any text
 Company    Any text
 Address    Any text
 Address2   Any text
 Address3   Any text
 Address4   Any text
 Address5   Any text
 Country    Any text
 Label      Either "None", "Tel", "Fax", "Home", "Work",
            "Mobile" or "E-mail"
 Number     Any text
 Label2     As Label
 Number2    Any text
 Label3     As Label
 Number3    Any text
 Label4     As Label
 Number4    Any text
 Marked     Either "TRUE" or "FALSE"
 Notes      Any text
 Notes2     Any text

The 'Type' and 'Label' (Label to Label4) fields need a value
that represents an item in the popup.

The 'Marked' field represents whether the checkbox is selected
("TRUE") or deselected ("FALSE").

The format of the ASCII file is selected from the Export-Format
popup in the @{" File Settings " Link File_Settings} requester.

The format defines what separates the fields and records. The
"Wordworth and Datastore" item specifies that each field should
be separated by a Tab character and each record by a Carriage
Return character.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}Import:@{UB} Imports the selected file into the relevant section.

@{B}Volumes:@{UB} Click to display volumes and assigns. Click again to
return to the file list.

@{B}Parent:@{UB} Click to display the contents of the parent drawer.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancel the file requester without importing any files.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Open command   " Link Open}
@{" Export command " Link Export}
@EndNode



@Node Export "Organiser Help: Export Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Export command@{UB}

Choose Export command (Project menu) to export Addresses from
Organiser.


@{fg highlight}Using Export@{fg text}

You can select the format in which addresses are exported, from
the "File Settings" requester.

The format defines what separates the fields and records. The
"Wordworth and Datastore" item, for example, specifies that each
field should be separated by a Tab character and each record by
a Carriage Return character.

If you are exporting the data for use with another, select
"Superbase (CSV)".


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}Export:@{UB} Exports the addresses to the selected filename and
destination.

@{B}Volumes:@{UB} Click to display volumes and assigns. Click again to
return to the file list.

@{B}Parent:@{UB} Click to display the contents of the parent drawer.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancel the file requester without exporting any files.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Save command   " Link Save}
@{" Import command " Link Import}
@EndNode


@Node Print "Organiser Help: Print Command"
@ToC Main

@{B}Print command@{UB}

Choose Print command (Project menu) to display a Print requester
from which you can set the options for printing your Organiser
project file. Alternatively, click the Print icon on the toolbar
or press Right Amiga-P.


@{fg highlight}Using Print@{fg text}

From the requester, select the options for your printout and
then click the Print button.

If you wish to store changes you made to the requester, but you
do not want a printout, click the requester Close gadget.

The settings made for each section are automatically stored.
Therefore, if you wish to print a different section, the
requester will display the last changes made for that section.


@{fg highlight}Print@{fg text}

@{B}Section:@{UB} From this popup list you can select the section you
wish to print:
  ° Calendar
  ° Diary
  ° Tasks
  ° Addresses
  ° Supplements

@{B}Layout:@{UB} Sets the layout, or style, of the printout.

For example, when printing the Tasks section you can choose to
print a full task list, a list of the daily tasks or the tasks
in priority order.

However, this option is not available when printing the Calendar
or Supplements.

@{B}Copies:@{UB} Specifies how many copies to print (normally 1).

@{B}Print to File:@{UB} If this check-box is selected Organiser
information will be printed, without any formatting, directly to
a file on disk instead of the printer.

When the Print button is clicked, you will be asked to specify
the name and destination of the file using a @{" file requester " Link FileRequester}.


@{fg highlight}Range@{fg text}

@{B}From/To:@{UB} Specifies the range of information to print.

For example, when printing Addresses you could print all of the
addresses (A to Z) or just a specific range (Jones to Smith).

@{B}All/Range:@{UB} Select All to ignore the range in the From/To text
gadgets and print all of the information. Select Range to print
the range specified in the From/To gadgets.

@{B}Filter:@{UB} Specifies certain items to print.

For example, you can use the filter to specify only the
"Completed Tasks" are printed (other filters for tasks are:
"Uncompleted Tasks or "Overdue Tasks").

This option is not available when printing the Calendar or Diary
sections.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}Print:@{UB} Prints the Organiser project information using the
options selected in this requester.

@{B}Settings:@{UB} Displays the @{" Print Settings " Link Print_Settings} requester from which you
can specify various layout settings.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels this Print requester.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Workbench printer preferences " Link WB_Printer_Prefs}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 When I print, the end of each line is printed on the following
  line.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_1}

2 Several strange characters are printed on the top of each
  page, or my printouts are just rubbish.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_2}

3 Why is it that every second page I print is only half
  full?  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_3}

4 I have the Centre option selected ("Print Settings" requester,
  Print command) but the page doesn't centre correctly.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_4}

5 When I try and print, Organiser keeps saying that the page
  size is too small, but I have "DIN A4" selected in my
  ("Workbench Printer Preferences" program).  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_5}
@EndNode


@Node Hide "Organiser Help: Hide Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Hide command@{UB}

Choose Hide command (Project menu) to hide the Organiser
display. Alternatively, click the window Close gadget at the top
left corner of the window or press Right Amiga-H.


@{fg highlight}Using Hide@{fg text}

When hidden, Organiser continues to operate in the background
and can be displayed again by:

 ° Double-clicking the Organiser icon on the Workbench desktop.

 ° Choosing the Organiser command from the Workbench Tools menu.

 ° Using the keyboard @{" hotkey " Link Tool_Types,34}.

 ° Activating the Organiser screen from the Exchange tool
   ('Workbench/Tools/Commodities' drawer).

You can also set Organiser to be hidden when it is started by
changing the @{" CX_POPUP tool type " Link Tool_Types,112} on the Organiser project icon
to 'CX_POPUP=NO'.
@EndNode



