@Node Quit "Organiser Help: 'Quit Organiser' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Quit Organiser" command@{UB}

Choose "Quit Organiser" command (Project menu) to exit Organiser
and return to the Workbench screen. Alternatively, press Right
Amiga-Q.


@{fg highlight}Using "Quit Organiser"@{fg text}

If you quit before you have @{" saved " Link Save} any changes made to a file,
Organiser will ask if you wish to save these changes before
quitting.


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 When I re-open my Organiser project file, Organiser displays
  reminders that I saw last time.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_File_4}

2 When I re-open my Organiser project file, some of the changes
  I made to the file are not there anymore.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_File_5}
@EndNode



@Node Edit_Menu "Organiser Help: Edit Menu"
@ToC Main
@{B}Edit Menu@{UB}

The Edit menu contains commands relating to the editing of
selected Organiser items.

@{" Cut          " Link Cut}
@{" Copy         " Link Copy}
@{" Paste        " Link Paste}
@{" Erase        " Link Erase}
@{" Erase Items  " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Undo         " Link Undo}
@{" Edit Details " Link Edit_Details}
@EndNode



@Node Cut "Organiser Help: Cut Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Cut command@{UB}

Choose Cut command (Edit menu) to cut the selected item and
place it on the clipboard. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-X.

This command is only available if you have a 'selected' item on
the Organiser page. A selected item is shown by a dotted line
under the first line of text.


@{fg highlight}Using Cut@{fg text}

You can use the Cut command to 'cut' the selected item (either
Diary Event, Address or Task) from the Organiser page and place
the information onto the @{" Amiga clipboard " Link Amiga_Clipboard}.

Once the information is on the clipboard, you can easily use it
with any other programs which also support the Amiga clipboard,
such as Datastore (the current version of Wordworth, however,
does not support the Amiga clipboard).

If a Diary Event has been 'cut' from the page, it can be
inserted into another day using the @{" Paste " Link Paste} command (Edit menu)
or into the Task section.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Copy command  " Link Copy}
@{" Paste command " Link Paste}
@EndNode



@Node Copy "Organiser Help: Copy Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Copy command@{UB}

Choose Copy command (Edit menu) to copy the selected item
and place it on the clipboard. Alternatively, press Right
Amiga-C.

This command is only available if you have a 'selected' item on
the Organiser page. A selected item is shown by a dotted line
under the first line of text.


@{fg highlight}Using Copy@{fg text}

You can use the Copy command to 'copy' the selected item (either
Diary Event, Address or Task) from the Organiser page and place
it onto the @{" Amiga clipboard " Link Amiga_Clipboard}.

Once the information is on the clipboard, you can easily use it
with any other programs which also support the Amiga clipboard,
such as Datastore (the current version of Wordworth, however,
does not support the Amiga clipboard).

If a Diary Event has been 'copied' from the page, it can be
inserted into another day using the @{" Paste " Link Paste} command (Edit menu)
or into the Task section.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Cut command   " Link Cut}
@{" Paste command " Link Paste}
@EndNode



@Node Paste "Organiser Help: Paste Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Paste command@{UB}

Choose Paste command (Edit menu) to place the contents of the
clipboard onto the Organiser page. Alternatively, press Right
Amiga-V.

This command is only available if you have information on the
@{" Amiga clipboard " Link Amiga_Clipboard}. Information is placed on the clipboard
using the @{" Cut " Link Cut} or @{" Copy " Link Copy} commands.


@{fg highlight}Using Paste@{fg text}

The Paste command inserts the text that is on the clipboard onto
the Organiser page. If an item is selected before a paste, it
will be overwritten with the contents of the clipboard.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Copy command " Link Copy}
@{" Cut command  " Link Cut}
@EndNode



@Node Amiga_Clipboard "Organiser Help: Amiga Clipboard"
@ToC Main
@{B}Amiga Clipboard@{UB}

Organiser uses the standard Amiga clipboard for @{" Cut " Link Cut}, @{" Copy " Link Copy}
and @{" Paste " Link Paste} (Edit menu).

This means you can easily exchange information between Organiser
and any other program which support the Amiga clipboard.

You can, for example, copy an address from a Datastore address
database and paste it into Organiser's Address section (the
current version of Wordworth, however, does not support the
Amiga clipboard).


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Copy command  " Link Copy}
@{" Cut command   " Link Cut}
@{" Paste command " Link Paste}
@EndNode



@Node Erase "Organiser Help: Erase Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Erase command@{UB}

Choose Erase command (Edit menu) to erase the selected item from
the Organiser page. Alternatively, press the Del key or click
the 'Trashcan' icon on the ribbon.

This command is only available if you have a 'selected' item on
the Organiser page. A selected item is shown by a dotted line
under the first line of text.

A requester will appear asking you to confirm the operation.
This requester, however, can be disabled by holding down the
Shift key before choosing the command, clicking the icon or
pressing Del.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Copy command          " Link Copy}
@{" Cut command           " Link Cut}
@{" 'Erase Items' command " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Paste command         " Link Paste}
@{" Undo command          " Link Undo}
@EndNode



@Node Erase_Items "Organiser Help: 'Erase Items' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Erase Items" command@{UB}

Choose "Erase Items" command (Edit menu) to Erase more than one
item from the Organiser page. This command is only available for
the Diary and Tasks sections.


@{fg highlight}Erasing Many Items@{fg text}

You can use this command in the Diary section for erasing
@{" Diary Events " Link Create_Diary_Event} between a range of dates. This is useful for
'purging' your diary of old information so that it opens, saves
and operates much quicker.

It is recommended that you do this on a fairly regular basis,
such as once a month or at the beginning of a new year.

@{" Repeating " Link Repeat_Options} events that occur outside the specified range
will not be erased. For example, birthday's will not be erased
unless you specified an end date that falls within the range.


When using this command in the Tasks section, you can erase any
@{" Tasks " Link Create_Task} that fall between a range of dates, or all 'completed
tasks'.


@{B}From:@{UB} Type in the start date of the items you want to erase.

@{B}To:@{UB} Type in the end date.

@{B}Completed Tasks Only:@{UB} This checkbox is only available when
erasing Tasks. Select if you wish to only erase 'completed
tasks'.

WARNING: You will not be able retreive any information that is
erased using this command, so be careful.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Cut command   " Link Cut}
@{" Copy command  " Link Copy}
@{" Erase command " Link Erase}
@{" Paste command " Link Paste}
@{" Undo command  " Link Undo}
@EndNode



@Node Undo "Organiser Help: Undo Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Undo command@{UB}

Choose Undo command (Edit menu) to replace an item that has just
been deleted.


@fg highlight}Using Undo@{fg text}

The Undo command applies to any item of information (events,
tasks or addresses) that has been @{" deleted " Link Erase} or @{" cut " Link Cut} from the
Organiser page.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Copy command  " Link Copy}
@{" Cut command   " Link Cut}
@{" Erase command " Link Erase}
@{" Paste command " Link Paste}
@EndNode



@Node Edit_Details "Organiser Help: 'Edit Details' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Edit Details" command@{UB}

Choose "Edit Details" command to edit the currently selected
item. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-E or double-click the
item on the page.

This command is only available if you have an item on the
Organiser page 'selected'. A selected item is shown by a dotted
line under the first line of text.


@{fg highlight}See@{fg text}

EDIT               REQUESTER

Address            @{" 'Address Details' requester          " Link Address_Details}
Detailed Address   @{" 'Detailed Address Details' requester " Link Detailed_Address_Details}
Diary Event        @{" 'Diary Event Details' requester      " Link Diary_Event_Details}
Task               @{" 'Task Details' requester             " Link Task_Details}
@EndNode



@Node Create_Menu "Orgainser Help: Create Menu"
@ToC Main
@{B}Create Menu@{UB}

The Create menu contains commands relating to the creation of
items in the current Organiser file.

@{" Diary Event... " Link Create_Diary_Event}
@{" Task...        " Link Create_Task}
@{" Address...     " Link Create_Address}
@{" Duplicate      " Link Duplicate}
@EndNode


@Node Create_Diary_Event "Organiser Help: 'Diary Event' Command"
@ToC "Main"
@{B}"Diary Event" command@{UB}

Choose "Diary Event" command (Create menu) to create a new Event
in the Diary section and display the @{" Diary Event Details " Link Diary_Event_Details}
requester. Alternatively, double-click a blank area of the Diary
page, click the "Create Diary Event" toolbar icon or press
Ctrl-E.


@{fg highlight}Using Diary Events@{fg text}

Diary events are items of information placed on a particular
day (with a time if you wish).


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Alarm Options' requester       " Link Alarm_Options}
@{" 'Auto Start Options' requester  " Link Auto_Start_Options}
@{" 'Diary Event Details' requester " Link Diary_Event_Details}
@{" 'Edit Details' command          " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Erase command                   " Link Erase}
@{" 'Erase Items' command           " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Hints And Tips                  " Link Hints_And_Tips}
@{" 'Repeat Options' requester      " Link Repeat_Options}


@{fg highlight}How Do I@{fg text}

@{" Add a birthday            " Link Add_Birthday}
@{" Change the view           " Link Views}
@{" Delete an event           " Link Erase}
@{" Delete all events         " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Edit an event             " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Import my Day-By-Day file " Link Import}
@{" Print the week's events   " Link Print_Events}
@{" Purge all events          " Link Erase_Items}
@EndNode



@Node Diary_Event_Details "Organiser Help: 'Diary Event Details' Requester"
@ToC "Main"
@{B}"Diary Event Details" requester@{UB}

Choose @{" Diary Event " Link Create_Diary_Event} command (Create menu) to create a new
Event in the Diary section and display the "Diary Event Details"
requester. Alternatively, double-click a blank area of the Diary
page, click the "Create Diary Event" toolbar icon or press
Ctrl-E.

This requester also appears when a diary event is being edited.
Double-click a diary event on the page or select it and choose
@{" Edit Details " Link Edit_Details} (Edit menu) to edit a diary event.


@{fg highlight}Using Diary Event Details Requester@{fg text}

Diary events are items of information placed on a particular
day (with a time if you wish).

You can spread an event over several days if you wish (like a
holiday), by typing a date into the "End Date" gadget (and "End
Time" if required).

All the elements on the requester are optional, so you do not
have to type information into every text gadget (this gives you
great flexibility when creating an event that).

Examples:
  EVENT              GADGETS TO USE

  Holiday            Date and "End Date"
  Meeting            Date and Time
  Long meeting       Date, Time and "End Time"
  Birthday           Date and "Every Year"


@{B}Title:@{UB} The title is essential and will appear in the first line
of the event on the diary page (it may go onto subsequent lines
if you type a long title).

@{B}Notes:@{UB} Additional notes for the event (which appear on the diary
page under the Title text).

@{B}Priority:@{UB} The priority determines the ordering of the events on
a day.

Priorities on timed events, however, are ignored as they are
always grouped together in time order (untimed events appearing
above them).

A Priority can be one of the following:
  ° Lowest
  ° Low
  ° Normal
  ° High
  ° Highest


@{fg highlight}Details@{fg text}

@{B}Date:@{UB} Type the start date of the event into this pop-up text
gadget. You can quickly select a date within the following week
from the pop-up.

@{B}End Date:@{UB} If necessary, type the end date of the event into this
pop-up text gadget. You can quickly select a date within the
following week from the pop-up.

@{B}Time:@{UB} If necessary, you can give the event a start time by
typing it into this text-gadget.

@{B}End Time:@{UB} If necessary, you can give the event an end time by
typing it into this text-gadget.

@{B}Every Year:@{UB} Select this option if you wish the event to be
repeated every year. This is especially useful for birthdays.

Alternatively, you could select '1 Year' from the "Repeat
Options" requester (Options button).

@{B}Summary:@{UB} This section gives a brief 'plain English' summary of
the event.


@{fg highlight}Options@{fg text}

@{B}Alarm:@{UB} Displays the @{" Alarm Options requester " Link Alarm_Options}. Set an alarm for
the event and when you are reminded.

@{B}Repeat:@{UB} Displays the @{" Repeat Options requester " Link Repeat_Options}. Sets when you
want the event repeated.

@{B}Auto Start:@{UB} Displays the @{" Auto Start Options requester " Link Auto_Start_Options}. Sets
the program or script to be started and what arguments are to be
sent to it.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Closes the requester and places the event on the diary page.

@{B}Create Another:@{UB} Places the event on the diary page and displays
another requester to create another event.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester and does not add the event onto
the diary page. Any events created before clicking the "Create
Another" button will not be cancelled.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Alarm Options' requester      " Link Alarm_Options}
@{" 'Auto Start Options' requester " Link Auto_Start_Options}
@{" 'Diary Event' command          " Link Create_Diary_Event}
@{" 'Edit Details' command         " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Erase command                  " Link Erase}
@{" 'Erase Items' command          " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Hints And Tips                 " Link Hints_And_Tips}
@{" 'Repeat Options' requester     " Link Repeat_Options}


@{fg highlight}How Do I@{fg text}

@{" Add a birthday            " Link Add_Birthday}
@{" Change the view           " Link Views}
@{" Delete an event           " Link Erase}
@{" Delete all events         " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Edit an event             " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Import my Day-By-Day file " Link Import}
@{" Print the week's events   " Link Print_Events}
@{" Purge all events          " Link Erase_Items}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 I have set several Diary Events with alarms but no alarm
  warning is ever displayed.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_2}

2 What is the Priority of an event for?  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_4}

3 I have too many events to fit on the Diary day and I,
  therefore, cannot see most of them.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_5}

4 When I try and create a Diary Event for my birthday (on 20
  June 1965), Organiser inserts it on the year 2065.  @{" ANSWER  " Link Answer_General_6}

5 When I type '10th April 1975' in the date gadget, Organiser
  changes it to the '10th April 2075'.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_7}
@EndNode



@Node Alarm_Options "Organiser Help: 'Alarm Options' Requester"
@ToC Main
@{B}Alarm Options@{UB}

Click the Alarm button on the @{" Diary Event Details " Link Create_Diary_Event} requester to
display the "Alarm Options" requester for setting how far in
advance the alarm will occur.


@{fg highlight}Using Alarms@{fg text}

This requester allows you to specify whether you wish to be
reminded before the event occurs. The period before the event
can also be specified along with how Organiser shows the alarm.

Organiser can display an on-screen reminder at a time or date
requested before the event.

As Organiser uses the system 'warning' signal to warn of an
alarm, you can specify whether you wish the Amiga to flash the screen
and/or beep (or even play a sound sample). You can set what you
wish the computer to do using the @{" Workbench Sound Preferences " Link WB_Sound_Prefs}.

To turn off the alarms deselect the "Alarms Active" checkbox on
the @{" General Settings " Link General_Settings} requester (Settings menu).


@{fg highlight}Alarm Options@{fg text}

@{B}Notify in Advance:@{UB} Type the number of minutes/hours/days/weeks
you wish to be notified in advance of the event. Then, select
whether the value is Minutes, Hours, Days or Weeks from the
pop-up list gadget.

@{B}Show On-Screen Reminder:@{UB} Select this option if you wish an
on-screen reminder to appear along with the system warning.

@{B}Summary:@{UB} This box will display a summary of the event in 'plain
English'.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Close the requester and use the current settings.

@{B}Clear:@{UB} Clear the alarm for the event and then close the
requester (you will be asked to confirm this).

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancel the requester without setting an alarm for the
event.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Auto Save                      " Link File_Settings}
@{" 'Create Diary Event' requester " Link Create_Diary_Event}
@{" Workbench Sound preferences    " Link WB_Sound_Prefs}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 I have set several Diary Events with alarms but no alarm
  warning is ever displayed.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_2}
@EndNode



@Node Repeat_Options "Organiser Help: 'Repeat Options' Requester"
@ToC Main
@{B}Repeat Options@{UB}

Click the Repeat button from the @{" Diary Event Details " Link Create_Diary_Event} requester
to display the "Repeat Options" requester for setting how often
the event will repeat.


@{fg highlight}Using Alarms@{fg text}

This requester allows you to specify whether you wish the event
to be repeated at regular intervals.

You can tell Organiser to repeat an event, for example,  on the
second Thursday of each month by first creating the Diary Event
on the second Thursday of the current month.

Then type 1 into the "Repeat Every" text gadget, select Month
from the popup and select the "On the Same Day and Week"
checkbox.

If an event is created on February 29th and repeated every
1 Year, it will appear on the 28th for non-leap years.

If an event is created on the 31st of a month and repeated every
1 Month, it will appear on the 30th or 28/29th for months that
do not have 31 days.


@{fg highlight}Repeat Options@{fg text}

@{B}Repeat Every:@{UB} Type the number of days/weeks/months/years the
event is repeated in this text-gadget. Then, select 'Days',
'Weeks', 'Months' or 'Years' from the popup gadget as
appropriate.

@{B}Until:@{UB} If the event is to stop repeating on a specific date,
type it in this text gadget.

@{B}On the Same Day and Week:@{UB} Select this checkbox if you wish the
event to repeat on the same day and week each month or year.

@{B}Example Dates:@{UB} This box shows a set of example dates for the
repeat options selected.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Close the requester and use the current settings.

@{B}Clear:@{UB} Clear the repeat options for the event and then close
the requester (you will be asked to confirm this).

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancel the requester without setting any repeat options
for the event.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Create Diary Event' requester " Link Create_Diary_Event}
@EndNode



@Node Auto_Start_Options "Organiser Help: 'Auto Start Options' Requester"
@ToC Main
@{B}Auto Start Options@{UB}

Click the "Auto Start" button from the @{" Diary Event Details " Link Create_Diary_Event}
requester to display the "Auto Start Options" requester for
specifying a program or script that you want Organiser to start
automatically. Alternatively, select a 'Diary Event' and click
the ribbon icon.


@{fg highlight}Using Auto Start@{fg text}

The Auto Start feature operates as if you were running a program
from the CLI (Shell). It allows you to specify the program or
script that you would like executed and the arguments to be
passed to it.

The program is then started at the date and time of the selected
Diary Event.

This feature is extremely useful for starting automatic backups,
or Wordworth to write a letter.

If you wish to start a script, you must either use the 'execute'
command or set the Script attribute on the file by choosing the
Information command from Workbench.

You can check that the Auto Start command works, by clicking the
"Test Auto Start" button.


@{fg highlight}Auto Start Options@{fg text}

@{B}Command:@{UB} Type the name of the program or script into this text
gadget. Alternatively, click Select and select the file from the
@{" file requester " Link FileRequester}.

@{B}Select:@{UB} Click to display a @{" file requester " Link FileRequester} from which you can
select a program or script to run.

@{B}Arguments:@{UB} Type any arguments that the program or script requires
in this text gadget. If one of the arguments is a file, click
Add to select it from a @{" file requester " Link FileRequester}.

@{B}Add:@{UB} Click to display a @{" file requester " Link FileRequester} from which you can
select a file argument which is then added to the end of the
Arguments text.

@{B}Ask Before Starting:@{UB} Specifies whether Organiser displays a
requester asking if the program is to be started.

@{B}Test Auto Start:@{UB} Click this button to test the running of the
program or script.

@{B}Summary:@{UB} Displays the event.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Closes the requester and sets the Auto Start Options for the
selected diary event.

@{B}Clear:@{UB} Clears the Auto Start event. (You will be asked to
confirm this.)

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester and ignores any changes made to
the requester.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Diary Event Details' requester " Link Diary_Event_Details}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 I have set a program to start automatically using the
  @{" Auto Start Options " Link Auto_Start_Options} requester, but it does not run.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_File_6}
@EndNode



@Node Create_Address "Organiser Help: Address Command"
@ToC "Main"
@{B}Address command@{UB}

Choose Address command (Create menu) to create a new address
in Organiser. This will display the @{" Address Details " Link Address_Details} requester.
Alternatively, double-click a blank area of the Address page,
click the "Create Address" toolbar icon or press Ctrl-A.


@{fg highlight}Using Address@{fg text}

There are two address requesters, one is brief and the other
detailed.

If the brief @{" Address Details " Link Address_Details} requester appears by default,
hold down the Shift key when creating the Address to display the
@{" Detailed Address Details " Link Detailed_Address_Details} requester.

The "Detailed Address Details" requester allows you to input
more information. For example, you can type up to four different
numbers.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Address Details' requester          " Link Address_Details}
@{" 'Detailed Address Details' requester " Link Detailed_Address_Details}
@{" 'Edit Details' command               " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Erase command                        " Link Erase}
@{" 'General Settings' requester         " Link General_Settings}
@{" Hints And Tips                       " Link Hints_And_Tips}


@{fg highlight}How Do I@{fg text}

@{" Change the view   " Link Views}
@{" Delete an address " Link Erase}
@{" Edit an address   " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Export addresses  " Link Export}
@{" Import addresses  " Link Import}
@{" Print addresses   " Link Print_Addresses}
@EndNode



@Node Address_Details "Organiser Help: 'Address Details' Requester"
@ToC "Main"
@{B}"Address Details" requester@{UB}

Choose @{" Address " Link Create_Diary_Event} command (Create menu) to create a new
Address in the Addresses section and display the "Address
Details" requester. Alternatively, double-click a blank area of
the Addresses page, click the "Create Address" toolbar icon or
press Ctrl-A.

This requester also appears when an address is being edited.
Double-click an address on the page or select it and choose
"Edit Details" (Edit menu) to display this requester.


@{fg highlight}Using Address Details Requester@{fg text}

There are two address requesters, one is brief and the other
detailed.

Hold down the Shift key when creating the Address to display the
@{" Detailed Address Details " Link Detailed_Address_Details} requester.

The "Detailed Address Details" requester allows you to input
more information. For example, you can type up to four different
numbers.

The "Address Details" requesters are the only requesters that
allow you to press Return to move from one text gadget to the
other. This makes it easy for you to input addresses quickly.

@{B}Name/Company:@{UB} Use the popup gadget to select if the address is
to appear as a Company address or Persons address.

Type the Person or Company's name in the following text-gadget.

@{B}Address:@{UB} Type the first line of the address in this gadget, if
necessary the text gadget underneath can be used for a second
address line.

@{B}Town:@{UB} Type the Town in this text gadget.

@{B}County:@{UB} Type the County in this text gadget.

@{B}Postcode:@{UB} Type the Postcode in this text gadget.

@{B}Tel:@{UB} The popup gadget shows what the number in the text gadget
refers to.

By default, the popup is set to "Tel", however you can change
this by selecting another item from the popup.

Type the number in the text-gadget to the right of the popup
gadget.

Popup items that are available are:
  ° None (Choose this option to disable the entry)
  ° Tel
  ° Home
  ° Work
  ° Fax
  ° Mobile
  ° E-Mail

There is another gadget underneath the first which can be used
to type another contact number.

@{B}Notes:@{UB} Type any additional information or notes in this text 
gadget.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Closes the requester and inserts the Address into
Organiser's Address section.

@{UB}Create Another:@{UB} Inserts the current address into Organiser's
Address section and leaves the requester open so that you can
input another one.

@{UB}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester without inserting the address.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Address command                      " Link Create_Address}
@{" 'Detailed Address Details' requester " Link Detailed_Address_Details}
@{" 'Edit Details' command               " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Erase command                        " Link Erase}
@{" 'General Settings' requester         " Link General_Settings}
@{" Hints And Tips                       " Link Hints_And_Tips}


@{fg highlight}How Do I@{fg text}

@{" Change the view   " Link Views}
@{" Delete an address " Link Erase}
@{" Edit an address   " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Export addresses  " Link Export}
@{" Import addresses  " Link Import}
@{" Print addresses   " Link Print_Addresses}
@EndNode


@Node Detailed_Address_Details "Organiser Help: 'Detailed Address Details' Requester"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Detailed Address Details" Requester@{UB}

Choose @{" Address " Link Create_Diary_Event} command (Create menu) to create a new
Address in the Addresses section and display the "Detailed
Address Details" requester. Alternatively, double-click a blank
area of the Addresses page, click the "Create Address" toolbar
icon or press Ctrl-A.

This requester also appears when an address is being edited.
Double-click an address on the page or select it and choose
"Edit Details" (Edit menu) to display this requester.


@{fg highlight}Using Detailed Address Details Requester@{fg text}

There are two address requesters, one is brief and the other
detailed.

Hold down the Shift key when creating the Address to display the
@{" Address Details " Link Address_Details} requester.

The brief "Address Details" requester allows you to input less
information. For example, you can only type up to two different
numbers.

The "Address Details" requesters are the only requesters that
allow you to press Return to move from one text gadget to the
other. This makes it easy for you to input addresses quickly.


@{B}Name:@{UB} Type the Person name or Company contact name into this
text gadget.

@{B}Company:@{UB} Type the Company name in this text gadget.

@{B}Position:@{UB} Type the persons position in this text gadget.

@{B}Show As:@{UB} Use this popup gadget to select if the address is to
appear in the Addresses section under the Name, Company or both.

This means that you do not have to duplicate addresses if you
want the information to appear under the Company and 'Contact
Name'.

@{B}Address:@{UB} Type the first line of the address in this gadget, if
necessary the text gadget underneath can be used for a second
address line.

@{B}Town:@{UB} Type the Town in this text gadget.

@{B}County:@{UB} Type the County in this text gadget.

@{B}Postcode:@{UB} Type the Postcode in this text gadget.

@{B}Country:@{UB} Type the Country in this text gadget.

@{B}Tel:@{UB} The popup gadget shows what the number in the text gadget
refers to.

By default, the popup is set to "Tel", however you can change
this by selecting another item from the popup.

Type the number in the text-gadget to the right of the popup
gadget.

Popup items that are available are:
  ° None (Choose this option to disable the entry)
  ° Tel
  ° Home
  ° Work
  ° Fax
  ° Mobile
  ° E-Mail

There are three other gadgets underneath the first which can be
used to type more contact numbers.

@{B}Marked:@{UB} This checkbox allows you to create a filter for more
important addresses. This option is only used by the @{" Print " Link Print}
requester.

@{B}Notes:@{UB} Type any additional information or notes in these text
gadgets.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Closes the requester and inserts the Address into
Organiser's Address section.

@{UB}Create Another:@{UB} Inserts the current address into Organiser's
Address section and leaves the requester open so that you can
input another one.

@{UB}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester without inserting the address.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Address command              " Link Create_Address}
@{" 'Address Details' requester  " Link Address_Details}
@{" 'Edit Details' command       " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Erase command                " Link Erase}
@{" 'General Settings' requester " Link General_Settings}
@{" Hints And Tips               " Link Hints_And_Tips}


@{fg highlight}How Do I@{fg text}

@{" Change the view   " Link Views}
@{" Delete an address " Link Erase}
@{" Edit an address   " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Export addresses  " Link Export}
@{" Import addresses  " Link Import}
@{" Print addresses   " Link Print_Addresses}
@EndNode


@Node Create_Task "Organiser Help: Task Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Task command@{UB}

Choose Task command (Create menu) to create a new task in
Organiser. This will display the @{" Task Details " Link Task_Details} requester.
Alternatively, double-click a blank area of the Task page,
click the "Create Task" toolbar icon or press Ctrl-T.


@{fg highlight}Using Tasks@{fg text}

A Task is usually an item which has a deadline. For example, a
school report. Once the deadline, or "Due Date", has been
passed, the task appears in red and the number of days overdue
are shown.

Tasks are shown, separated in priority order and can be
'completed' by clicking a small box on the page.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Task command                         " Link Create_Task}
@{" 'Edit Details' command               " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Erase command                        " Link Erase}
@{" 'Erase Items' command                " Link Erase_Items}


@{fg highlight}How Do I@{fg text}

@{" Add an task                " Link Add_Task}
@{" Delete a task              " Link Erase}
@{" Delete a range of tasks    " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Delete all completed tasks " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Edit a task                " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Print tasks                " Link Print_Tasks}
@EndNode


@Node Task_Details "Organiser Help: 'Task Details' Requester"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Task Details" requester@{UB}

Choose @{" Task " Link Create_Task} command (Create menu) to create a new
Task in the Tasks section and display the "Task Details"
requester. Alternatively, double-click a blank area of the Tasks
page, click the "Create Task" toolbar icon or press Ctrl-T.

This requester also appears when an Task is being edited.
Double-click an task on the page or select it and choose "Edit
Details" (Edit menu) to display this requester.


@{fg highlight}Using Task Requester@{fg text}

The "Task Details" requester allows you to insert tasks onto the
page. These tasks are separated in priority order.

A deadline can also be assigned to the task. If the deadline is
passed, Organiser will display it in red and show how many days
it is overdue.

When a task has been inserted onto the page, a square box
appears to the left. If this box is clicked with the mouse, a
tick appears - this is used to 'complete' the task. You can,
however, edit the task and select the Completed checkbox instead.


@{B}Title:@{UB} Type the title of the task into this gadget.

@{B}Priority:@{UB} Select a priority for the task from this popup. The
Task page automatically separates the different priorities.

@{B}Notes:@{UB} Type any additional information or notes in this text 
gadget.

@{B}Due Date:@{UB} Type a date to be used for the deadline into this
gadget. Days in the following week can be selected using the
popup.

@{B}Completed:@{UB} Select this checkbox if you want to 'complete' or
'tick' the task off. The @{" Erase Items " Link Erase_Items} command (Edit menu) can
then be used to erase all completed tasks.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Closes the requester and inserts the task into
Organiser's Task section.

@{UB}Create Another:@{UB} Inserts the current task into Organiser's Task
section and leaves the requester open so that you can input
another one.

@{UB}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester without inserting the task.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Task command                         " Link Create_Task}
@{" 'Edit Details' command               " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Erase command                        " Link Erase}
@{" 'Erase Items' command                " Link Erase_Items}


@{fg highlight}How Do I@{fg text}

@{" Add an task                " Link Add_Task}
@{" Delete a task              " Link Erase}
@{" Delete a range of tasks    " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Delete all completed tasks " Link Erase_Items}
@{" Edit a task                " Link Edit_Details}
@{" Print tasks                " Link Print_Tasks}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 When I type '10th April 1975' in the date gadget, Organiser
  changes it to the '10th April 2075'.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_7}
@EndNode


@Node Duplicate "Organiser Help: Duplicate Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Duplicate command@{UB}

Choose Duplicate (Create menu) to make a copy of the selected
item. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-D.

This command is only available if an item on the Organiser page
is 'selected'. A selected item is shown by a dotted line under
the first line of text.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Amiga Clipboard " Link Amiga_Clipboard}
@{" Cut command     " Link Cut}
@{" Copy command    " Link Copy}
@{" Paste command   " Link Paste}
@EndNode


@Node Locate_Menu "Orgainser Help: Locate Menu"
@ToC Main
@{B}Locate Menu@{UB}

The Locate menu contains commands which allow you to locate
various items in the current Organiser file.

@{" Go To Date... " Link Go_To_Date}
@{" Supplements   " Link Supplements}
@{" Find...       " Link Find}
@{" Find Again    " Link Find_Again}
@{" Today         " Link Today}
@{" This Week     " Link This_Week}
@{" This Month    " Link This_Month}
@{" Next Week     " Link Next_Week}
@EndNode


@Node Go_To_Date "Organiser Help: 'Go To Date' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Go To Date" command@{UB}

Choose "Go To Date" command (Locate menu) to jump to a specific
date in the Diary section. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-J or
click the toolbar icon.


@{fg highlight}Using Go To Date@{fg text}

Type the date that you wish to jump to in the Date text gadget
and press the Return key. If the date exists, the pages will
turn to the appropriate day in the Diary section.

Use the popup to quickly select a day within the next week.

Hold down the Shift key when choosing the command to jump to the
'selected' day. A selected day is shown by a dotted line under
the date.


@{B}Date:@{UB} Type the date to which you wish to jump, or select a date
from the popup list gadget. The popup contains dates for the
following week for quick access.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}Go To:@{UB} Click to jump to the date in the Date gadget.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancel the requester without jumping to another date.


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 When I type '10th April 1975' in the date gadget, Organiser
  changes it to the '10th April 2075'.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_7}
@EndNode



@Node Supplements "Organiser Help: The Supplements Pull Down Menu"
@ToC Main
@{B}Supplements pull down menu@{UB}

Choose Supplements command (Locate menu) to display a pull down
sub-menu containing a list of all the Supplement files that have
been placed in the 'Organiser/Supplements' drawer.


@{fg highlight}Using The Supplements Menu@{fg text}

Choose the Supplement you want from the pull down sub-menu to
automatically turn to the appropriate place in the Supplements
section. (If the item 'No Supplements' appears, you will have to
@{" install a Supplement " Link Install_Supps} first.)

You can browse through the Supplements section by clicking on
the 'Page Corner' icons in the bottom corner of either page.
Alternatively, press , (the comma key) or . (the full stop key).


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Creating supplements   " Link Create_Supps}
@{" Installing supplements " Link Install_Supps}
@{" Removing supplements   " Link Remove_Supps}
@EndNode



@Node Find "Organiser Help: Find Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Find command@{UB}

Choose Find command (Locate menu) to display a requester from
which you can search for a particular word or words.
Alternatively, press Right Amiga-F or click the toolbar icon.


@{fg highlight}Using Find@{fg text}

First select the section in which you wish to search from the
Search popup (select "All Sections" if you wish to search the
entire Organiser file). Searching is faster if the specify a
particular section rather than the entire file.

If you specify a particular section the first popup will be
enabled allowing you to search a particular text gadget. For
example, just the Country text gadget in the Address section.

Next, type the text you wish to search for in the text gadget
and from the second popup, select the level of search. For
example, whether the specified field Contains the text or just
'Begins With' the text.

All searches are case-insensitive which means, for example, that
Organiser will find angling, Angling or ANGLING.


@{fg highlight}AmigaDOS Patterns@{fg text}

The Find command uses AmigaDOS patterns to let you create
complicated search patterns.

For example, you can search for either 'Health' or 'Teeth' by
typing "(health | teeth)" into the text gadget and selecting
Contains.

The '|' character specifies OR and is typed by pressing Shift-\.
Some other conditions are:

CONDITION     SEARCH FOR

?             A wildcard character. For example "t?ps" will find
              't@{B}i@{UB}ps', 't@{B}o@{UB}ps' or 't@{B}a@{UB}ps'.

#?            Many wildcards. For example, "#?ant#?" will find
              'eleph@{B}ant@{UB}s' or 'sl@{B}ant@{UB}ing'.

~             Excluding. For example, "~(#?s)" will find
              everything that does not end with an 's'.

|             OR. For example, "(John | Tom | Phil)" will find
              information that contains any of the three names.

The narrower you make the search, the quicker it will be.
Therefore, try and restrict the search, if possible, to a
particular section and field.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}Find:@{UB} Click to find the first occurrence of the text specified.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester without finding any text.

@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Find Again' command " Link Find_Again}
@EndNode



@Node Find_Again "Organiser Help: 'Find Again' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Find Again" command@{UB}

Choose "Find Again" command (Locate menu) to repeat the @{" Find " Link Find}
last performed. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-G.

This command will be unavailable if you have not previously used
the Find command.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Find command " Link Find}
@EndNode


@Node Today "Organiser Help: Today Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Today command@{UB}

Choose Today command (Locate menu) to turn to the current day in
the Diary section. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-T or click
the Diary tab.


@{fg highlight}Using The Today Command@{fg text}

This command will turn to the Diary section, and move to the
current day.

The current date is shown on the ribbon bar and is set from the
@{" Set Date and Time " Link Set_Date_And_Time} requester each time Organiser is started.

If the "Set Date and Time" requester does not appear on startup,
select the "Set Date and Time on Startup" checkbox from
@{" General Settings " Link General_Settings} (Settings menu) and restart the macine.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Next Week' command " Link Next_Week}
@{" 'This Month' command " Link This_Month}
@{" 'This Week' command " Link This_Week}
@EndNode



@Node This_Week "Organiser Help: 'This Week' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"This Week" command@{UB}

Choose "This Week" command (Locate menu) to turn to the
current week in the Diary section. Alternatively, press
Right Amiga-W.


@{fg highlight}Using The "This Week" Command@{fg text}

This command will turn to the Diary section, and move to the
current week. If the Diary is currently in the 'Day per Page'
view, the view is changed to view a week across both pages.

The current date is shown on the ribbon bar and can be set from
the @{" Set Date and Time " Link Set_Date_And_Time} requester each time Organiser is started.

If the "Set Date and Time" requester does not appear on startup,
select the "Set Date and Time on Startup" checkbox from
@{" General Settings " Link General_Settings} (Settings menu) and restart the macine.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Today command        " Link Today}
@{" 'Next Week' command  " Link Next_Week}
@{" 'This Month' command " Link This_Month}
@EndNode



@Node This_Month "Organiser Help: 'This Month' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"This Month" command@{UB}

Choose "This Month" command (Locate menu) to turn to the
Calendar section and display the current month. Alternatively,
press Right Amiga-M.


@{fg highlight}Using The "This Month" Command@{fg text}

This command will turn to the Calendar section, and move to view
the current month.

The current date is shown on the ribbon bar and can be set from
the @{" Set Date and Time " Link Set_Date_And_Time} requester each time Organiser is started.

If the "Set Date and Time" requester does not appear on startup,
select the "Set Date and Time on Startup" checkbox from
@{" General Settings " Link General_Settings} (Settings menu) and restart the macine.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Today command       " Link Today}
@{" 'Next Week' command " Link Next_Week}
@{" 'This Week' command " Link This_Week}
@EndNode



@Node Next_Week "Organiser Help: 'Next Week' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Next Week" command@{UB}

Choose "Next Week" command (Locate menu) to turn to next
week in the Diary section.


@{fg highlight}Using The "Next Week" Command@{fg text}

This command will turn to the Diary section, and move to next
week. If the Diary is currently in the 'Day per Page' view, the
view is changed to view a week across both pages.

The current date is shown on the ribbon bar and can be set from
the @{" Set Date and Time " Link Set_Date_And_Time} requester each time Organiser is started.

If the "Set Date and Time" requester does not appear on startup,
select the "Set Date and Time on Startup" checkbox from
@{" General Settings " Link General_Settings} (Settings menu) and restart the macine.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Today command        " Link Today}
@{" 'This Month' command " Link This_Month}
@{" 'This Week' command  " Link This_Week}
@EndNode



@Node Settings_Menu "Organiser Help: Settings Menu"
@ToC Main
@{B}Settings Menu@{UB}

The Settings menu contains commands which allow you to customise
Organiser for the way you like to work.

@{" Auto Save?                " Link Auto_Save}
@{" At a Glance?              " Link At_a_Glance}
@{" Create Icons?             " Link Create_Icons}
@{" Change Settings - General " Link General_Settings}
@{" Change Settings - File    " Link File_Settings}
@{" Change Settings - Print   " Link Print_Settings}
@{" Change Settings - Font    " Link Font_Settings}
@{" Load Settings...          " Link Load_Settings}
@{" Save Settings             " Link Save_Settings}
@{" Save Settings As...       " Link Save_Settings}
@EndNode



@Node Auto_Save "Organiser Command: 'Auto Save' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Auto Save" command@{UB}

Choose "Auto Save" command (Settings menu) to turn On or Off
the 'Auto Save' feature. A tick denotes that the feature is on.
Choose again to turn off "Auto Save".


@{fg highlight}Using Auto Save@{fg text}

When "Auto Save" is on, Organiser will automatically save your
file after a specific period.

To set the auto save delay type a value (in minutes) into the
@{" 'Change Settings'-File " Link File_Settings} command (Settings menu).

If you always want "Auto Save" on, choose the @{" Save Settings " Link Save_Settings}
command (Settings menu). The settings file can be saved using a
different name and desination by choosing @{" Save Settings As " Link Save_Settings_As}
(Settings menu).


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'File Settings' requester  " Link File_Settings}
@{" Hints And Tips             " Link Hints_And_Tips}
@{" Save command               " Link Save}
@{" 'Save As' command          " Link Save_As}
@{" 'Save Settings' command    " Link Save_Settings}
@{" 'Save Settings As' command " Link Save_Settings_As}
@EndNode



@Node At_a_Glance "Organiser Help: 'At a Glance' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"At a Glance" command@{UB}

Choose "At a Glance" command (Settings menu) to abbreviate
the information being viewed. A tick denotes that the feature is
on. Choose again to turn off "At a Glance". Alternatively, press
the Space Bar or click the ribbon icon on the far left to toggle
this feature On and Off.


@{fg highlight}Using At a Glance@{fg text}

If you have a lot of text in Organiser, it is sometimes
necessary to abbreviate the information so that you can see all
of the events.

Only the text in the Title gadget is shown in the Diary and
Tasks section, all other text is hidden.

However, when you are viewing the Addresses section, "At a
Glance" only displays the name and first number and is therefore
ideal for a quick 'telephone directory style' listing.

If you always want "At a Glance" on, choose the @{" Save Settings " Link Save_Settings}
command (Settings menu). The settings file can be saved using a
different name and desination by choosing @{" Save Settings As " Link Save_Settings_As}
(Settings menu).
@EndNode



@Node Create_Icons "Organiser Help: 'Create Icons' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}Create Icons@{UB}

Choose "Create Icons" command (Settings menu) to save icons
with any project or settings file. A tick denotes that the
feature is on. Choose again to turn off "Create Icons".


@{fg highlight}Using Create Icons@{fg text}

The icons that are saved for project and settings files are
stored in the drawer 'ENVARC:Organiser'. These icons can be
edited so that the @{" tool types " Link Tool_Types} or even the image can be changed.

When starting Organiser from Workbench (as opposed to the
Shell), you should turn on this command.
@EndNode



@Node General_Settings "Organiser Help: The 'General Settings'"
@ToC Main
@{B}The "General Settings"@{UB}

Choose General command from the "Change Settings" pull down
menu (Settings menu) to display the "General Settings" requester.


@{fg highlight}Using General Settings@{fg text}

From this requester you can customise various parts of the
program. If you then choose "Save Settings" (Settings menu),
Organiser will use these changes each time it starts up.


@{fg highlight}Time@{fg text}

@{B}Always Assume AM:@{UB} If this option is selected, any time typed in
the Organiser Time gadgets (@{" Diary Event Details " Link Diary_Event_Details} requester)
will be AM. This can be overriden by specifying AM or PM after
the time.

@{B}Assume PM if Before:@{UB} When this option selected, any time typed
in the Organiser Time gadgets (@{" Diary Event Details " Link Diary_Event_Details}
requester) will be PM if they are before the time specified in
this settings requester. This can be overriden by specifying AM
or PM after the time.

@{B}24 Hour Clock:@{UB} Select this option to show times in the 24 hour
format.

@{B}Set Date and Time on Startup:@{UB} Select this checkbox to display
the @{" Set Date and Time requester " Link Set_Date_And_Time} each time Organiser is started.

If you have an Amiga with no built-in clock, you will need to
ensure this checkbox is selected.


@{fg highlight}Options@{fg text}

@{B}Alarms Active:@{UB} Select this checkbox to turn the Alarm
feature on. If it is not selected, no @{" alarm reminders " Link Diary_Event_Details} or
@{" warnings " Link WB_Sound_Prefs} will appear.

@{B}Alarm On for New Diary Events:@{UB} When this checkbox is
selected, each new @{" Diary Event " Link Diary_Event_Details} will have the alarm set
automatically.

@{B}Detailed Addresses as Standard:@{UB} Select this checkbox to display
the large @{" Detailed Address Details requester " Link Detailed_Address_Details}, each time you
@{" create an address " Link Create_Address}, by default.

If the detailed address requester is set to display by default,
hold down the Shift key when creating an Address to use the
brief @{" Address Details requester " Link Address_Details} instead.

@{B}Show Fortune Cookies:@{UB} Select this option if you wish to get an
Organiser Fortune Cookie each time you start the program.

Cookies can be words of wisdom, Anecdotes or Organiser Tips.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Closes the requester and uses the current settings.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester and ignores any changes made to
the requester.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Save Settings' command    " Link Save_Settings}
@{" 'Save Settings As' command " Link Save_Settings_As}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 I have set several Diary Events with alarms but no alarm
  warning is ever displayed.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_2}
@EndNode


@Node File_Settings "Organiser Help: The 'File Settings'"
@ToC Main
@{B}The "File Settings"@{UB}

Choose File command from the "Change Settings" pull down
menu (Settings menu) to display the "File Settings" requester.


@{fg highlight}Using File Settings@{fg text}

From this requester you can customise various parts of the
program relating to files. If you then choose "Save Settings"
(Settings menu), Organiser will use these changes each time it
starts up.


@{fg highlight}Saving@{fg text}

@{B}Create Backups:@{UB} Select this option to create a backup of your
file when you save it. Backup files are suffixed by the letters
'.bak' and are copies of the previous revision of the file.

@{B}Auto Save Delay:@{UB} Set the time delay in minutes that you want
Organiser to wait before automatically saving your file.

To start "Auto Save", choose @{" Auto Save " Link Auto_Save} (Settings menu) so a
tick appears next to the command name.



@{fg highlight}Export@{fg text}

Format: Select the format of the exported address file from this
pop-up. The format specifies which characters in the file are
used to distinguish between fields and records.

Available formats:
  ° Wordworth and Datastore
  ° Digita Mailshot Plus
  ° Superbase (CSV)

If you are using the exported address file with Wordworth or
Datastore, you must select the "Wordworth and Datastore" format.

Most other programs will use the "Superbase (CSV)" format. (CSV
stands for 'Comma Separated Values'.)


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Closes the requester and uses the current settings.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester and ignores any changes made to
the requester.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Save Settings' command    " Link Save_Settings}
@{" 'Save Settings As' command " Link Save_Settings_As}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 I cannot import any names and addresses into Organiser.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_File_3}

2 I have set several Diary Events with alarms but no alarm
  warning is ever displayed.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_2}
@EndNode



@Node Print_Settings "Organiser Help: The 'Print Settings'"
@ToC Main
@{B}The "Print Settings"@{UB}

Choose Print command from the "Change Settings" pull down
menu (Settings menu) to display the "Print Settings" requester.

This requester can also be called up by clicking the 'Settings'
button on the @{" Print requester " Link Print}.



@{fg highlight}Using Print Settings@{fg text}

From this requester you can customise the printing options used
by Organiser. If you then choose "Save Settings" (Settings
menu), Organiser will use these changes each time it starts up.


@{fg highlight}Page Layout@{fg text}

@{B}Format:@{UB} Choose the format of the page that you wish to print
from this popup.

There are many different formats of page to choose from. The
"Full Page" format prints using the "Page Format" specified in
the @{" Workbench Printer preferences " Link WB_Printer_Prefs}, all the other formats are
various Filofax style sizes.

@{B}Centre:@{UB} When printing in a format other than "Full Page", select
this checkbox centre the printout on the page.

@{B}Print Cut Lines:@{UB} When printing in a format other than "Full Page",
select this checkbox to print lines between the 'Crop marks' on each corner of the printed page.

This is useful if you have to use scissors to cut out the page
from the paper, instead of a guilletine.

@{B}Separate List Pages:@{UB} Select this option to use separate pages
for each: calendar year, diary month, task priority and address
'letter'.


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}OK:@{UB} Closes the requester and uses the current settings.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester and ignores any changes made to
the requester.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Save Settings' command    " Link Save_Settings}
@{" 'Save Settings As' command " Link Save_Settings_As}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 When I print, the end of each line is printed on the following
  line.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_1}

2 Several strange characters are printed on the top of each
  page, or my printouts are just rubbish.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_2}

3 Why is it that every second page I print is only half
  full?  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_3}

4 I have the Centre option selected ("Print Settings" requester,
  Print command) but the page doesn't centre correctly.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_4}

5 When I try and print, Organiser keeps saying that the page
  size is too small, but I have "DIN A4" selected in my
  ("Workbench Printer Preferences" program).  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_5}
@EndNode



@Node Font_Settings "Organiser Help: The 'Font Settings'"
@ToC Main
@{B}The "Font Settings"@{UB}

Choose Font command from the "Change Settings" pull down
menu (Settings menu) to display the "Font Settings" requester.


@{fg highlight}Using Font Settings@{fg text}

From this requester you can customise the fonts used by
Organiser for the Organiser page, requesters and menus. If you
then choose "Save Settings" (Settings menu), Organiser will use
these changes each time it starts up.

To change a particular font, select the type you wish to change
from the Fonts list and click Edit. Select a new font and size,
then click OK.

Fonts: Select the font type you wish to edit from the list. You
can choose to edit the following:
  ° Text Font
  ° Heading Font
  ° Requester Heading Font
  ° Requester Gadget Font
  ° Screen Font


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}Edit:@{UB} Click this button to change the font, size and style for
the selected Font type, using the standard ASL font requester.

@{B}OK:@{UB} Closes the requester and uses the current settings.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels the requester and ignores any changes made to
the requester.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Save Settings' command    " Link Save_Settings}
@{" 'Save Settings As' command " Link Save_Settings_As}
@EndNode


@Node Load_Settings "Organiser Help: 'Load Settings' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Load Settings" command@{UB}

Choose "Load Settings" command (Settings menu) to load a
settings file previously saved from the @{" Save Settings As " Link Save_Settings_As}
command (Settings menu).


@{fg highlight}Using Save Settings@{fg text}

The settings file that is used when the program starts can be
specified from the @{" SETTINGS tool type " Link Tool_Types} on the program or
project icon.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{"'Save Settings As' command " Link Save_Settings_As}
@EndNode


@Node Save_Settings "Organiser Help: 'Save Settings' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Save Settings" command@{UB}

Choose "Save Settings" command (Settings menu), to save the
current settings to the default settings file which is used each
time you start Organiser.


@{fg highlight}Using Save Settings@{fg text}

The settings that are saved in the settings file are as follows:

 ° The current view for the Diary, Addresses and Task sections.
 ° All the items on the "Settings menu"
 ° All the items in the settings requesters.
 ° Contents of the Print and Find requesters.
 ° Paths for Open, Save, "Print To File", Import and Export
   @{" file requesters " Link FileRequester}.

The settings file that is used when the program starts can be
specified from the @{" SETTINGS tool type " Link Tool_Types} on the program or
project icon.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{"'Save Settings As' command " Link Save_Settings_As}
@EndNode


@Node Save_Settings_As "Organiser Help: 'Save Settings As' Command"
@ToC Main
@{B}"Save Settings As" command@{UB}

Choose "Save Settings As" command (Settings menu), to save
the current settings to a settings file under a different name
and in a different destination.


@{fg highlight}Using Save Settings@{fg text}

The settings that are saved in the settings file are as follows:

 ° The current view for the Diary, Addresses and Task sections.
 ° All the items on the "Settings menu"
 ° All the items in the settings requesters.
 ° Contents of the Print and Find requesters.
 ° Paths for Open, Save, "Print To File", Import and Export
   @{" file requesters " Link FileRequester}.

The "Save Settings As" command will display a @{" file requester " Link FileRequester} from
which you can specify the name and destination of the file.

The settings file that is used when the program starts can be
specified from the @{" SETTINGS tool type " Link Tool_Types} on the program or
project icon.

Any settings file that is saved using the "Save Settings As"
command (Settings Menu) can be reloaded at any time by choosing
@{" Load Settings " Link Load_Settings} (Settings menu).


@{fg highlight}Buttons@{fg text}

@{B}Save:@{UB} Saves the settings file using the specified name and
destination.

@{B}Volumes:@{UB} Click to display volumes and assigns. Click again to
return to the file list.

@{B}Parent:@{UB} Click to display the contents of the parent drawer.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancel the file requester without saving the file.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Load Settings' command    " Link Load_Settings}
@{" 'Save Settings As' command " Link Save_Settings_As}
@EndNode



@Node Help_Menu "Organiser Help: Help Menu"
@ToC Main
@{B}Help Menu@{UB}

The Help menu contains commands which call up the various
sections in Organiser's on-line help.

@{" How Do I...?    " Link How_Do_I}
@{" How To Use Help " Link How_To_Use_Help}
@{" Contents        " Link Main}
@{" Tutorial        " Link Tutorial}
@{" Shortcuts       " Link Shortcuts}
@{" Index           " Link Org_Index}
@{" Troubleshooting " Link Troubleshooting}
@EndNode



@Node What's_New "Organiser Help: What's New"
@ToC Main
@{B}What's New@{UB}

As this is version 1.0 of Organiser, there is nothing new.

However, if you have any ideas or suggestions of new features or
improvements that you would like to see in the next version then
please let us know at the Digita @{" Technical Support " Link Tech_Support} address.
@EndNode



@Node Tech_Support "Organiser Help: Technical Support"
@ToC Main
@{B}Getting Technical Support@{UB}

Before contacting the Digita Technical Support, please read the
@{" Troubleshooting " Link Troubleshooting} section.


@{fg highlight}To contact Digita Technical Support in the UK@{fg text}

@{B}Call:@{UB}  0891 616 944 weekdays from 11am to 5pm. Calls are charged
       at 36p per minute cheap rate and 48p per minutes at all
       other times. Be sure to ask the permission of the
       telephone owner before calling.

@{B}Fax:@{UB}   01 395 268 893.


@{B}Write:@{UB} Organiser Technical Support Department
       Digita International Limited
       Black Horse House
       Exmouth
       Devon EX8 1JL


@{B}NET:@{UB}   support@digita.demon.co.uk


@{B}CIX:@{UB}   digita@cix

       Conferences - 'digita' for general chat.
                   - 'digita.tech' for technical support.
                     Mail 'digita@cix' for access to this
                     closed conference, quoting your
                     registration number.


@{B}CIS:@{UB}   100031,3032

If you are outside the UK, contact your local Digita
representative.


@{fg highlight}When phoning, please have ready the following@{fg text}

1 Organiser version number (Refer About command, Project menu)
2 Description of your computer system
3 Detailed description of your problem


@{fg highlight}When writing, please provide the following@{fg text}

1 A stamped addressed padded envelope when enclosing disks for
  replacing or testing.
2 Organiser version number (Refer About command, Project menu)
3 Description of your computer system
4 Detailed description of your problem, with example files
  and/or printouts.


@{B}Important@{UB}
Unfortunately, under no circumstances can Digita provide either
telephone or written support to unregistered users.
@EndNode



