4 What is the Priority of an event for?  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_4}

5 I have too many events to fit on the Diary day and I,
  therefore, cannot see most of them.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_5}

6 When I try and create a Diary Event for my birthday (20 June
  1965), Organiser inserts it on the year 2065.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_6}


@{" Return to Troubleshooting Contents " Link Troubleshooting}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_Print_1 "Organiser Help: Printing Problem 1"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q When I print, the end of each line is printed on the following
  line.@{UB}

A This could be caused by either, or both, of the following
  reasons:
   1 If your "Right Margin" is set too high in your
     @{" Workbench Printer Preferences " Link WB_Printer_Prefs} program, the printer will
     automatically wrap the end of each line onto the following
     one.

   2 You are using a "Print Pitch" ("Workbench Printer
     Preferences" program) that is not supported by your
     printer. The fonts in some printers are only supported in
     certain pitches, therefore the best pitch to use is Pica
     (10 cpi).
  
  See Chapter 6.2, "Setting Up Your Printer" for more detailed
  information.


@{" More Printing Problems " Link Trouble_Print}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_Print_2 "Organiser Help: Printing Problem 2"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q Several strange characters are printed on the top of each
  page, or my printouts are just rubbish.@{UB}

A You may have the wrong printer driver selected in your
  @{" Workbench Printer Preferences " Link WB_Printer_Prefs} program and so the printer
  will not understand the control codes being sent to it.
  
  See Chapter 6.2, "Setting Up Your Printer", for information on
  selecting the correct printer driver.


@{" More Printing Problems " Link Trouble_Print}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_Print_3 "Organiser Help: Printing Problem 3"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q Why is it that every second page I print is only half full?@{UB}

A This could be caused by one of three reasons:

   1 The "Page Length" (@{" Workbench Printer Preferences " Link WB_Printer_Prefs} program)
     is too high and the printer is printing onto the second
     page thinking it is the first.

   2 The "Right Margin" is too high and the end of each line is
     wrapped onto the next. This will effectively double the
     number of lines actually being printed.

   3 The "Print Pitch" selected is not supported by your printer
     in the font you are using. This will make the lines wrap
     onto each following line and, as in 2 above, double the
     lines being printed.

  See Chapter 6.2, "Setting Up Your Printer", for more
  information.


@{" More Printing Problems " Link Trouble_Print}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_Print_4 "Organiser Help: Printing Problem 4"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q I have the Centre option selected ("Print Settings" requester,
  Print command) but the page doesn't centre correctly.@{UB}

A You either have your margins set incorrectly
  (@{" Workbench Printer Preferences " Link WB_Printer_Prefs} program) or you may be using
  a "Print Pitch" of "Fine (15-17cpi)" which is not supported by
  many printers.
  
  See Chapter 6.2, "Setting Up Your Printer", for information
  about print pitches.


@{" More Printing Problems " Link Trouble_Print}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_Print_5 "Organiser Help: Printing Problem 5"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q When I try and print, Organiser keeps saying that the page
  size is too small, but I have "DIN A4" selected in my
  (@{" Workbench Printer Preferences " Link WB_Printer_Prefs} program).@{UB}

A The Margins in your @{" Workbench Printer Preferences " Link WB_Printer_Prefs} program
  are set incorrectly.
  
  Both the Left and Right margins are measured from the left
  edge of the page. This means you will have to work out how
  many characters can be printed along a page and subtract the
  right margin you wish to actually use before typing it into
  the "Right Margin" gadget.
  
  See Chapter 6.2, "Setting Up Your Printer", for instructions
  on how to set up margins.


@{" More Printing Problems " Link Trouble_Print}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_File_1 "Organiser Help: File Problem 1"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q I cannot open my Supplements.@{UB}

A Do not use the Open command (Project menu) when trying to
  insert a Supplement.
  
  You need to quit Organiser first and then move the appropriate
  Supplement file into the 'Supplements' drawer ('Organiser'
  disk on floppy disk). Organiser will only look in the
  'Supplements' drawer when it first starts, to see what
  Supplements files are available.
  
  For more information see Chapter 10.10, "Supplements Section".


@{" More File Problems " Link Trouble_File}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_File_2 "Organiser Help: File Problem 2"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q I have Day-By-Day and I want to use my project file with
  Organiser but I cannot get Organiser to open it.@{UB}

A When importing Day-By-Day information into Organiser, use the
  Import command (Project menu). The Open command is only for
  Organiser project files.


@{" More File Problems " Link Trouble_File}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_File_3 "Organiser Help: File Problem 3"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q I cannot import any names and addresses into Organiser.@{UB}

A You are probably missing the header record in your import
  file. The header record is always the first record (at the top
  of your file) which describes which fields are used and what
  their names are.


@{" More File Problems " Link Trouble_File}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_File_4 "Organiser Help: File Problem 4"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q When I re-open my Organiser project file, Organiser pops up
  reminders that I saw last time.@{UB}

A You probably just turned off your machine the last time you
  used Organiser without @{" Saving your file " Link Save}. Whether Organiser
  has already shown you the Alarm Reminders or not is saved with
  the project.

  You should therefore always use the @{" Quit Organiser " Link Quit} command
  (Project menu) before reseting your machine so that all
  changes are saved to the file.

  Alternatively, set the "Auto Save Delay" text gadget
  (@{" File Settings requester " Link File_Settings}, Settings menu) to 0. This will
  save your project file everytime a change has been made to it.


@{" More File Problems " Link Trouble_File}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_File_5 "Organiser Help: File Problem 5"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q When I re-open my Organiser project file, some of the changes
  I made to the file are not there anymore.@{UB}

A You probably just turned off your machine the last time you
  used Organiser without @{" Saving your file " Link Save}.

  You should therefore always use the @{" Quit Organiser " Link Quit} command
  (Project menu) before reseting your machine so that all
  changes are saved to the file.

  Alternatively, set the "Auto Save Delay" text gadget
  (@{" File Settings requester " Link File_Settings}, Settings menu) to 0. This will
  save your project file everytime a change has been made to it.


@{" More File Problems " Link Trouble_File}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_File_6 "Organiser Help: File Problem 6"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q@{UB} I have set a program to start automatically using the
  @{" Auto Start Options " Link Auto_Start_Options} requester, but it does not run.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_File_6}

A Some programs require the current directory to be in the
  location of the program.

  Using a text editor, create a two line script which changes
  into the program's directory and then runs the program. Now
  execute this script from the @{" Auto Start Options " Link Auto_Start_Options} requester.
  
  For example:
    cd Work:Applications/Datastore
    DSProg

  If you are trying to run Wordworth, you must select the
  'WwProg' file and not the 'Wordworth' file.


@{" More File Problems " Link Trouble_File}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_Speed_1 "Organiser Help: Speed Problem 1"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q When I turn to the Calendar section, it seems to take quite a
  while to draw all the information on the screen. This didn't
  used to happen.@{UB}

A When there are a lot of diary events that are repeated every
  month or year, the Calendar can take longer to work out every
  day that contains an event. This may happen with the
  "Celebrity Birthdays" Diary Theme which has a lot of yearly
  events.


@{" More Speed Problems " Link Trouble_Speed}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_Speed_2 "Organiser Help: Speed Problem 2"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q The Supplements section takes a while to appear when I click
  the Supplements section tab. Why?@{UB}

A Organiser has to work out the formatting of every Supplement
  so that it can display them correctly (the size of page is
  dependant upon the screen mode and the font you use).

  Some of the Supplements have quite a few pages of information
  and can therefore take a while to format. If the speed
  concerns you, do not use so many Supplements or use
  Supplements which do not have a lot of pages.
  
  For example, the "National Dialling Codes" Supplement is very
  big, but major towns and cities have also been placed in a
  separate Supplement which is smaller and quicker to use.


@{" More Speed Problems " Link Trouble_Speed}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_General_1 "Organiser Help: General Problem 1"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q I want to set an alarm for a task. How do I do it?@{UB}

A Select the task, so that a dotted line appears beneath its
  first line, and choose Cut (Edit menu). Then move to the Diary
  section, choose Paste (Edit menu) and edit the event to define
  an alarm.


@{" More General Problems " Link Trouble_General}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_General_2 "Organiser Help: General Problem 2"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q I have set several Diary Events with alarms but no alarm
  warning is ever displayed.@{UB}

A First, you should ensure that your system date and time is
  correct (the ribbon at the top of the Organiser display shows
  the current date and time). You can change the setting using
  the "Workbench Time Preferences" program.
  
  Every time your Organiser starts, a requester should appear
  for you to set the current date and time. If this does not
  happen select the "Set Date and Time on Startup" checkbox on
  the "General Settings" requester ("Change Settings"-General
  command, Settings menu).
  
  If the date and time is correct, then you may not have the
  alarms option turned on. Ensure that the "Alarms Active"
  checkbox is selected ("Change Settings"-General command,
  Settings menu).


@{" More General Problems " Link Trouble_General}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_General_3 "Organiser Help: General Problem 3"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q How do I type an address with more than two telephone numbers?@{UB}

A Hold down the Shift key when you use the "Create Address"
  command. This reveals the detailed "Address Details" requester.

  You can set this detailed requester to appear by default by
  selecting the "Detailed Addresses as Standard" checkbox from
  "General Settings" ("Change Settings"-General command,
  Settings menu). With this option selected, the Shift key will
  display the brief "Address Details" requester.


@{" More General Problems " Link Trouble_General}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_General_4 "Organiser Help: General Problem 4"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q What is the Priority of an event for?@{UB}

A The Diary event priority is used to order the events on a
  particular day.
  
  Events which have a time are always ordered in time order and
  the Priority is ignored. They also appear below any event
  which does not have a specific time.
  
  Events which do not have a specific time are placed at the top
  and ordered with the Highest priority appearing at the top,
  the Lowest at the bottom.


@{" More General Problems " Link Trouble_General}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_General_5 "Organiser Help: General Problem 5"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q I have too many events to fit on the Diary day and I,
  therefore, cannot see most of them.@{UB}

A There are two ways to see the other events:
   1 Choose "At A Glance" (Settings menu) to only see the first
     line of the Title. This will allow you to see several more
     events on the day.

   2 Select the day so that a dotted grey line appears under the
     day name, and then change the view so that more space is
     available for your events. Use the ribbon icons or use the
     keys 1, 2, 3 or 4 to change between different views.


@{" More General Problems " Link Trouble_General}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_General_6 "Organiser Help: General Problem 6"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q When I try and create a Diary Event for my birthday (20 June
  1965), Organiser inserts it on the year 2065.@{UB}

A Organiser will not let you create an event or task before the
  year 1980. Therefore, insert your birthday on the current year
  and not the year you were born.


@{" More General Problems " Link Trouble_General}
@EndNode


@Node Answer_General_7 "Organiser Help: General Problem 7"
@ToC Main
@{B}Q When I type '10th April 1975' in the date gadget, Organiser
  changes it to the '10th April 2075'.@{UB}

A Organiser will not let you create an event or task before the
  year 1980.


@{" More General Problems " Link Trouble_General}
@EndNode


@Node Print_Addresses "Organiser Help: Printing Addresses"
@ToC Main
@{B}Printing Addresses@{UB}

Choose @{" Print " Link Print} command (Project menu) to display the Print
requester. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-P or click the
toolbar icon.


@{fg highlight}Step 1@{fg text}

Select 'Addresses' from the Section pop-up gadget and select the
layout of the printout from the Layout pop-up:
  ° Address List
  ° Address Book
  ° Address Cards
  ° Telephone List


@{fg highlight}Step 2@{fg text}

Select the Range radio button and type a range of addresses in
the From and To text gadgets. To print one persons address, type
their name in both gadgets.

Type 1 in the Copies text gadget and ensure that the 'Print to
File' checkbox is deselected.


@{fg highlight}Step 3@{fg text}

Click the "Settings" button to display the @{" Print Settings " Link Print_Settings}
requester and select 'Standard Filofax (6ľ" tall x 3ľ")' from
the Format pop-up.

Finally, make sure the @{"Workbench Printer preferences" Link WB_Printer_Prefs} are set
correctly and click Print.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Address command (Create menu) " Link Create_Address}
@{" Print command                 " Link Print}
@{" 'Print Settings' requester    " Link Print_Settings}
@EndNode


@Node Print_Events "Organiser Help: Printing Events"
@ToC Main
@{B}Printing Events@{UB}

Choose @{" Print " Link Print} command (Project menu) to display the Print
requester. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-P or click the
toolbar icon.


@{fg highlight}Step 1@{fg text}

Select 'Diary' from the Section pop-up gadget and select the
"Daily List" layout from the Layout pop-up. Other layouts are:

LAYOUT         PRINTOUT

Daily List     List of events.
Day Per Page   Each day on separate page.
Week Per Page  Each week on separate page.
Week to View   Week on two pages (all days the same).
Working Week   Week on two pages (smaller weekends).


@{fg highlight}Step 2@{fg text}

Select the Range radio button and type a range of dates in the
From and To text gadgets. To print out an entire years events,
select All.

Type 1 in the Copies text gadget and ensure that the 'Print to
File' checkbox is deselected.


@{fg highlight}Step 3@{fg text}

Click the "Settings" button to display the @{" Print Settings " Link Print_Settings}
requester and select 'Full Page' from the Format pop-up.

Finally, make sure the @{"Workbench Printer preferences" Link WB_Printer_Prefs} are set
correctly and click Print.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" 'Diary Event' command (Create menu) " Link Create_Diary_Event}
@{" Print command                       " Link Print}
@{" 'Print Settings' requester          " Link Print_Settings}
@EndNode


@Node Print_Tasks "Organiser Help: Printing Tasks"
@ToC Main
@{B}Printing Tasks@{UB}

Choose @{" Print " Link Print} command (Project menu) to display the Print
requester. Alternatively, press Right Amiga-P or click the
toolbar icon.


@{fg highlight}Step 1@{fg text}

Select 'Tasks' from the Section pop-up gadget and then select
the All radio button to ensure that all Task Priorities are
printed.

Next, select Uncompleted from the Filter popup as we only want
to print out Tasks that are yet to be done.



@{fg highlight}Step 1@{fg text}

Type 1 in the Copies text gadget and ensure that the 'Print to
File' checkbox is deselected.

Click the "Settings" button to display the @{" Print Settings " Link Print_Settings}
requester and select 'Full Page' from the Format pop-up.

Finally, make sure the @{"Workbench Printer preferences" Link WB_Printer_Prefs} are set
correctly and click Print.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Task command (Create menu) " Link Create_Task}
@{" Print command              " Link Print}
@{" 'Print Settings' requester " Link Print_Settings}
@EndNode


@Node Add_Birthday "Organiser Help: Adding a Birthday"
@ToC Main
@{B}Adding a birthday@{UB}

Choose @{" Diary Event " Link Create_Diary_Event} command (Project menu) or double-click
a day in Organiser's Diary section to display the "Diary Event
Details" requester.


@{fg highlight}Step 1@{fg text}

Type the persons name in the Title text gadget, together with
any additional information in the Notes gadget.

Now, type their birthday date in the Date text gadget and leave
the other gadgets blank. When typing the date, insert it in the
current year and not the year they were born (refer to
@{" General Troubleshooting - 6 " Link Answer_General_6} for an explanation).


@{fg highlight}Step 2@{fg text}

Select the "Every Year" check box gadget so that the birthday
will be repeated  on the same date every year.


@{fg highlight}Step 3@{fg text}

To ask Organiser to remind you a day before the birthday click
the Alarm button to display the "Alarm Options requester".

Type 1 in the Notify text gadget and select Day from the popup.
Now ensure the "Show On-Screen Reminder" checkbox is selected
and click OK.

Click OK again, to insert the event onto the Diary page and
close the requester.

Finally, @{" Save " Link Save} your file after making changes to it.


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 When I try and create a Diary Event for my birthday (20 June
  1965), Organiser inserts it on the year 2065.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_6}
@EndNode


@Node Add_Task "Organiser Help: Adding a Task"
@ToC Main
@{B}Adding a Task@{UB}

Choose @{" Task " Link Create_Task} command (Project menu) or double-click on the
Task page to display the "Task Details" requester.


@{fg highlight}Step 1@{fg text}

Type 'Geography Report' in the Title text gadget and then type
'10 June' in the "Due Date" gadget for the reports's deadline.


@{fg highlight}Step 2@{fg text}

Next select High from the Priority popup and click "Create
Another".

The "Create Another" button will insert the current task into
the Tasks section and clear the requester for another task.


@{fg highlight}Step 3@{fg text}

This time, type 'Buy more shampoo' in the Title gadget and
select a Low Priority.

Leave the Due Date gadget balnk as we are not bothered when the
task is done.

Click OK to insert this second task onto the Task page and close
the requester.

Finally, @{" Save " Link Save} your file after making changes to it.


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 When I type '10th April 1975' in the date gadget, Organiser
  changes it to the '10th April 2075'.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_General_7}
@EndNode


@Node Views "Organiser Help: Organiser Views"
@ToC Main
@{B}Views in Organiser@{UB}

Organiser can display the information on the page using
different views so that you can choose how much information is
shown. (This is not available for Calendar and Supplements.)

Each item of information in a section can also be condensed
using the @{" At a Glance " Link At_a_Glance} command (Settings menu).


@{fg highlight}At A Glance@{fg text}

Below is a table showing what will amount of information will be
seen, for each section, when the "At a Glance" feature is On or
Off.

SECTION      ON                        OFF

Calendar     N/A                       N/A
Diary        First line of text        All information
Tasks        First line of text        All information
Addresses    Telephone number listing  All information
Supplements  N/A                       N/A

The Diary and Addresses sections can use "At a Glance" together
with the normal Page Views.


@{fg highlight}Page Views@{fg text}

@{B}Diary Section:@{UB} There are four views in a group of four icons on
the ribbon bar.

From left to right these are: Day per page, Working week per
double page (short weekends), Week per double page, Week per
page.

@{B}Addresses Section:@{UB} There are three views shown on the ribbon
bar.

From left to right: All address information, Lines of address
are compressed and no Notes are shown, Address compressed onto
two lines and only some numbers are shown (again no Notes).
@EndNode


@Node Create_Supps "Organiser Help: Creating Supplements"
@ToC Main
@{B}Creating Supplements@{UB}

Organiser supplements are text files which can be produced using
a word processor that can save files in ASCII format (such as
Wordworth), or a text editor.


@{fg highlight}Creating A Supplement@{fg text}

i. When creating a supplement using Wordworth, type the text as
you would normally, only pressing the Return key at the end of
each paragraph.

Ensure that the "End of Paragraph" radio button on the "File
Settings" requester is selected ("Change Settings"-File,
Settings menu) before saving your Supplement file into the
Supplements drawer.

ii. When using a text editor, type each paragraph as a single
line, pressing the Return key only at the end of a paragraph.
Then, save the Supplement file in the Supplements drawer.


@{fg highlight}Using Tabs@{fg text}

The first line of a supplement can be used to define the tab
stops for the Supplement. Tab stops are used for indenting text,
or setting columns.

When defining the tab line:

1.  The tab character is used to divide the page equally into
the given number of parts (note that an extra tab is
automatically added to the end).

2.  A tab stop marker (" ^ ") is placed at the positions where
you would like an actual tab stop to occur. (Press Shift-6 to
type a tab stop marker.)


Example tab lines:

To set a tab position that will create a column down the centre
of the page, type:

<TAB>^

To define three equally spaced columns type:

<TAB>^<TAB>^<TAB>^

To place a single tab stop close to the right of the page, use
the following tab line:

<TAB><TAB><TAB><TAB>^


Trial and error may be necessary to find the best place for the
tabs.

To use the tab positions, simply insert a tab character into the
Supplement text whenever you want to move to the next tab stop.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Installing Supplements " Link Install_Supps}
@{" Removing Supplements   " Link Remove_Supps}
@EndNode


@Node Install_Supps "Organiser Help: Installing Supplements"
@ToC Main
@{B}Installing Supplements@{UB}

Supplements are like the pre-printed information pages you get
in a real Filofax, and with Organiser you can just as easily
insert and remove them.

1  Always quit Organiser before moving a Supplement.

2  A Supplement is moved into Organiser by dragging its file
from the 'Supplements Storage' drawer into the 'Supplements'
drawer.

Floppy Disk Users: The 'Supplements Storage' drawer is located
on the OrganiserExtras disk, the 'Supplements' drawer on the
Organiser disk.

3  Re-start Organiser to view the Supplements.

4  Turn to a particular Supplement by choosing the Supplement
file from the @{" Supplements pull down menu " Link Supplements} (Locate menu).

5  Turn pages by clicking the turned page corner on the bottom
of each page or press , (comma) to turn to the previous page, or
. (full point) to turn to the next.

6  Supplements will effect the performance of Organiser. The
fewer the better!

7  You can @{" create your own Supplements " Link Create_Supps} with Digita Wordworth
or any other word processor by just saving the Supplement as an
"ASCII Text" file. (Ensure that you have "At End Of Paragraph"
selected from "File Settings", Settings menu.)


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Creating Supplements " Link Create_Supps}
@{" Removing Supplements " Link Remove_Supps}
@EndNode


@Node Remove_Supps "Organiser Help: Removing Supplements"
@ToC Main
@{B}Removing Supplements@{UB}

A supplement file can be removed by moving it out of the
'Supplements' drawer.

Floppy disk users: Just select the Supplement file you wish to
remove (from the 'Supplements' drawer on the 'Organiser' disk)
and choose Delete from the Workbench Icons menu.

Hard disk users: Drag the Supplement file from the Supplements
drawer back into its appropriate drawer in the 'Supplements
Storage 95' drawer (do not delete Supplements as you may wish to
use them in the future).


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Creating Supplements   " Link Create_Supps}
@{" Installing Supplements " Link Install_Supps}
@EndNode


@Node Create_Disk "Organiser Help: Creating A Separate Files Disk"
@ToC Main
@{B}Creating a separate files disk@{UB}

To create a separate disk for storing your Organiser files you
will need to 'format' a blank disk for use with the Amiga. This
tutorial will show you how this is done.


@{fg highlight}Step 1@{fg text}

Place a blank disk into the internal drive and select the
@{B}DF0:????@{UB} icon that appears on the Workbench screen

(The @{B}DF0:@{UB} means 'device floppy 0' or internal drive, and the @{B}????@{UB}
means that the Amiga does not understand the disk as it has not
yet been formatted.)


@{fg highlight}Step 2@{fg text}

Once the disk icon has been selected, choose the "Format Disk"
command (Workbench-Icons menu).

A requester will appear with the following options:

@{B}OK:@{UB} Formats the disk for use with the Amiga.

@{B}OK Quick:@{UB} Formats a previously formatted Amiga disk. This option
is much quicker if you have already done a full format.

@{B}Cancel:@{UB} Cancels requester.


Workbench 2.1 and above will have additional items:

@{B}New Volume Name:@{UB} This is the name given to the disk (for
example, 'MyFiles')

@{B}Put Trashcan:@{UB} This adds a trashcan icon to the disk. It is best
to deselect this.

@{B}Fast File System:@{UB} This makes Opening and Saving to the disk much
quicker. It also gives you 80Kb more space. Make sure that this
is selected.

@{B}International Mode:@{UB} This is for foreign languages where accented
characters are used in filenames. Leave this deselected.


Workbench 3.0 and above will have the additional item:

@{B}Directory Cache:@{UB} This option speeds up disk access by
remembering what was in the directories. It however uses up
memory so leave it deselected.


@{fg highlight}Step 3@{fg text}

Once formatted, the disk can be viewed from any @{"file requester" Link FileRequester}
by typing the name of the disk into the Drawer text gadget
followed by a colon (:). (The colon tells the Amiga to ask for a
disk of the specified name.)

For example, typing 'MyFiles:' into the Drawer gadget will
display a requester asking you to 'Insert Volume MyFiles in any
drive'.
@EndNode



@Node Open_File_Sep_Disk "Organiser Help: Opening A File From A Separate Disk"
@ToC Main
@{B}Opening a file from a separate floppy disk@{UB}

Choose Open command (Project menu) to display the file
requester, from this you can select the disk you wish to open
from and the file to open.

To view the contents of a separate disk, type the disk name into
the Drawer text gadget followed by a colon (:). The disk name is
displayed under the disk icon on the Workbench screen when the
disk is inserted into a disk drive.

When the Return key is pressed, you will be prompted to insert
this disk, after which you will be shown its contents.

For example, if you have a disk that was named 'MyFiles' you
would need to type @{I}MyFiles:@{UI} into the Drawer text gadget on the
"Select File To Open" requester before pressing the Return key.

See also:
@{"Opening A Previously Saved File" Link Open}
@{"Creating A Separate Files Disk " Link Create_disk}
@EndNode



@Node Delete_File "Organiser Help: Deleting A File"
@ToC Main
@{B}Deleting a file@{UB}

Choose Open or "Save As" command (Project menu) to display a
@{" file requester " Link FileRequester}.

To delete a file, select it from the list gadget and choose the
Delete command from the file requester Control menu.
@EndNode



@Node Save_File_Sep_Disk "Organiser Help: Saving Onto A Separate Disk"
@ToC Main
@{B}Saving a file onto a separate floppy disk@{UB}

Choose "Save As" command (Project menu) to display the
standard @{" file requester " Link FileRequester}.

Then, insert the disk that you wish to save the file on, into the
disk drive and click the disk name that appears at the top of the list.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Save command                   " Link Save}
@{" 'Save As' command              " Link Save_As}
@{" Creating a separate files disk " Link Create_Disk}
@EndNode



@Node Hints_And_Tips "Organiser Help: Hints And Tips"
@ToC Main
@{B}Hints And Tips@{UB}

In this section you will find a series of hints and tips that
will make your use of Organiser more useful and enjoyable.

If you have any of your own, please let our @{" Technical Support " Link Tech_Support}
team know so that we can add them to this section for other
users.


@{fg highlight}Starting Organiser@{fg text}

1  @{" Save " Link Save_As} your Organiser project file into the 'SYS:WBStartup'
   drawer if you want Organiser to automatically start whenever
   your machine is reset.

2  If you are auto starting Organiser, and prefer the Organiser
   screen to be hidden, change the @{" CX_POPUP tool type " Link Tool_Types,112} on the
   Organiser project icon to 'CX_POPUP=NO'.

3  Change the icon tool types for @{" hot key " Link Tool_Types,65}, @{" popup " Link Tool_Types,112} and
   @{" priority " Link Tool_Types,117}.


@{fg highlight}Using Organiser@{fg text}

1  Press Right Amiga-, (comma) or Right Amiga-. (full stop) keys
   in Date, Time and Number text gadgets to increase or decrease
   values. Use the Shift key for bigger increments.

2  Type the number of days, hours or minutes into "End Date" or
   "End Time" text gadgets for automatic calculation of values.

3  Type the day of week, 'today', 'tomorrow' or 'yesterday' into
   date gadgets for easy entry of date.

4  Shift double-click the page in the Addresses section to
   display the @{" Detailed Address Details " Link Detailed_Address_Details} requester.
  
   This requester allows you to enter more information for the
   address. (There is a preference setting in @{" General Settings " Link General_Settings}
   to make this the default.)

5  If you need to type an address that has a double-barrelled
   surname, press Alt-Space between the surnames so that all the
   words are treated as one.

6  Use the control key in text gadgets, for requester gadget
   shortcuts.

7  There are keyboard shortcuts in system requesters so that you
   can press the first letter of a button label to activate it.

   System requesters are requesters that appear in the top left
   corner of the screen and have a patterned background.

8  Use , (comma) and . (full stop) to turn pages backward and
   forward. Also use Tab and Shift-Tab for moving to the
   previous or next section.

9  Always use the @{" Quit Organiser " Link Quit} command (Project menu) before
   turning off your machine as you will lose any information that
   you may have typed.

10 When you add a birthday, insert it on the current year and
   not the year the person was born. This is because Organiser
   does not allow you to type a year before 1980.
@EndNode



@Node WB_Printer_Prefs "Organiser Help: Workbench Printer Preferences"
@ToC Main
@{B}Workbench Printer Preferences@{UB}

The Printer preferences program allows you to control the set up
of the printer connected to your Amiga.

Floppy disk users: The Workbench Printer Preferences program can
be found in the 'Prefs' drawer on the 'Organiser' disk.

Hard disk users: The Workbench Printer Preferences program can
be found in the 'Prefs' drawer on the 'Workbench' or 'System'
partition of your hard disk.


@{fg highlight}Using The Workbench Printer Preferences@{fg text}

Before Printing, you must ensure that the printer is set up
correctly.

1. Select the appropriate driver for your printer from the
"Printer Drivers" list, as a rough guide follow the table below.
If your printer is not listed it may have an emulation that
corresponds to one of the following.
   
PRINTER                             PRINTER DRIVER

Epson Compatible 9 pin              'EpsonX'
Epson Compatible 24 pin             'EpsonQ'
Canon Bubblejet                     'CanonBJ10'
Hewlett Packard Compatible DeskJet  'HP_DeskJet'
Hewlett Packard Compatible LaserJet 'HP_LaserJet'


2. Follow the tables below for changing other values in the
requester:

PRINT PITCH       LEFT MARGIN  RIGHT MARGIN

Pica (10 cpi)          5            75  
Elite (12 cpi)         6            90
Fine (15-17 cpi) - Do not use this settings as it may give
                   unpredictable results.


PAPER SIZE   PRINT SPACING  PAPER LENGTH

A4                 6             65
A4                 8             86
US Letter          6             60
US Letter          8             80

Click Save to save these settings permanently to disk.

Refer to your Workbench User Guide for any further information
on printing and Printer preferences.


@{fg highlight}See Also@{fg text}

@{" Print command              " Link Print}
@{" 'Print Settings' requester " Link Print_Settings}


@{fg highlight}Troubleshooting@{fg text}

1 When I print, the end of each line is printed on the following
  line.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_1}

2 Several strange characters are printed on the top of each
  page, or my printouts are just rubbish.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_2}

3 Why is it that every second page I print is only half
  full?  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_3}

4 I have the Centre option selected ("Print Settings" requester,
  Print command) but the page doesn't centre correctly.  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_4}

5 When I try and print, Organiser keeps saying that the page
  size is too small, but I have "DIN A4" selected in my
  ("Workbench Printer Preferences" program).  @{" ANSWER " Link Answer_Print_5}
@EndNode



@Node WB_Sound_Prefs "Organiser Help: Workbench Sound Preferences"
@ToC "Main"
@{B}Workbench Sound Preferences@{UB}

The Workbench Sound preferences allows you to determine that
type of sound that is produced by your Amiga when a warning
occurs (for example, an alarm or error).


@{fg highlight}Using Sound Preferences@{fg text}

The Amiga can just flash the screen and/or produce a sound. This
sound can be just a 'beep' or a sound sample (small piece of
recorded sound).

Do not turn off both "Flash Display" and "Make Sound" as this
may cause you to miss a prompt.


@{B}Sound Type:@{UB} Select Beep and edit the parameters below ("Sound
Volume", "Sound Pitch", "Beep Length") for a simple sound.
Alternatively, select "Sampled Sound".

Sound Volume: Select the sound volume of the 'Beep' of 'Sample'.
1 is quite, 64 is loud.

@{B}Sound Pitch:@{UB} Select the pitch of the 'Beep' of 'Sample'. Do not
set the pitch too low as it affects how long it takes to play
the sound.

@{B}Beep Length:@{UB} Only available when "Sound Type" is set on 'Beep',
this slider gadget selects the duration of the sound. 1 is
short, 100 is long.

@{B}Select Sample:@{UB} Click this button to display a @{" file requester " Link FileRequester}
from which you can select a sound sample.

Floppy disk users - Type 'OrganiserExtras:' in the Drawer text
gadget, press Return and click the 'Sampled Sounds' drawer. In
this drawer you will find a "Harp" sample. Select it and click
OK.

Hard disk users - Locate the Organiser drawer and click the
'Sampled Sounds' drawer. In this drawer you will find a "Harp"
sample. Select it and click OK.

@{B}Test Sound:@{UB} Once your settings are correct and your sample has
been selected, click this button to test the sound.

Click Save to save your settings to disk.
@EndNode
